const e={id:"fungal-infections",name:"Fungal Infections",icon:"🍄",category:"IDSA 2016 Candidiasis & Aspergillosis Guidelines · Antifungal Stewardship",overview:{definition:"Invasive fungal infections (IFIs) are life-threatening infections caused by opportunistic fungi, primarily Candida species (candidemia, invasive candidiasis) and Aspergillus species (invasive pulmonary aspergillosis, disseminated aspergillosis). Candidemia is the 4th most common bloodstream infection in US hospitals with crude mortality of 25–40%. Invasive aspergillosis carries mortality >50% in immunocompromised hosts. Early antifungal therapy and source control are critical determinants of outcome.",epidemiology:"Candidemia: Incidence 8–10 per 100,000 hospitalizations. C. albicans remains most common (~50%) but C. glabrata (15–25%), C. parapsilosis (10–15%), C. tropicalis (5–10%), and C. krusei (2–5%) are rising. C. auris is an emerging MDR threat with >90% fluconazole resistance and outbreaks in healthcare facilities. ICU patients account for ~40% of candidemia episodes. Invasive aspergillosis: Primarily affects severely immunocompromised patients — prolonged neutropenia (>10 days), allogeneic HSCT recipients, solid organ transplant recipients on high-dose immunosuppression, and patients receiving ≥0.3 mg/kg/day prednisone equivalent for ≥3 weeks. Incidence 5–25% in high-risk hematologic malignancy patients. A. fumigatus is the dominant species (>90% of invasive disease).",keyGuidelines:[{name:"IDSA 2016 Clinical Practice Guideline for the Management of Candidiasis",detail:"Comprehensive guideline covering candidemia, chronic disseminated candidiasis, and organ-specific invasive candidiasis. KEY CHANGES from prior: echinocandins elevated to first-line for candidemia in all patients (previously fluconazole preferred in non-critically ill). Fluconazole de-escalation encouraged once species and susceptibility confirmed. Strong recommendation for ophthalmologic exam in all candidemia patients. CVC removal recommended within 24–48 hours when feasible.",sourceIds:["idsa-candidiasis"]},{name:"IDSA 2016 Practice Guidelines for Diagnosis and Management of Aspergillosis",detail:"Guidelines for invasive pulmonary aspergillosis, chronic pulmonary aspergillosis, and allergic forms. Voriconazole remains first-line for invasive aspergillosis. Isavuconazole non-inferior per SECURE trial. Combination therapy (voriconazole + echinocandin) may benefit some patients per subgroup analysis of the voriconazole-anidulafungin combination study. Therapeutic drug monitoring for voriconazole strongly recommended (trough 1–5.5 mcg/mL).",sourceIds:["idsa-aspergillosis"]},{name:"ESCMID 2012 Candida Guideline (Non-neutropenic Adults)",detail:"European candidiasis guidance reinforcing echinocandin-first therapy for candidemia, early catheter removal, daily blood cultures to clearance, and fundoscopy/echo-based metastatic workup. Useful supporting guidance alongside IDSA, though it predates newer agents and C. auris-specific recommendations.",sourceIds:["escmid-2012-candida"]}],landmarkTrials:[{name:"Reboli et al., NEJM 2007 — Anidulafungin vs Fluconazole for Candidemia",detail:"Landmark RCT (ROCKER study) establishing echinocandin superiority over fluconazole for candidemia. Anidulafungin had higher global response rate (75.6% vs 60.2%, p=0.01) at end of IV therapy. This trial, combined with similar micafungin and caspofungin data, was the primary evidence driving echinocandins to first-line status in the 2016 IDSA guidelines. Mortality trended lower with anidulafungin but did not reach statistical significance.",sourceIds:["reboli-2007-anidulafungin"]},{name:"Herbrecht et al., NEJM 2002 — Voriconazole vs Amphotericin B for Invasive Aspergillosis",detail:"Pivotal RCT establishing voriconazole as first-line for invasive aspergillosis. Voriconazole had significantly better response rates (52.8% vs 31.6%) and survival (70.8% vs 57.9% at 12 weeks) compared to amphotericin B deoxycholate. Also demonstrated better tolerability. This trial fundamentally changed aspergillosis treatment from amphotericin B to voriconazole as standard of care.",sourceIds:["herbrecht-2002-voriconazole"]},{name:"Maertens et al., Lancet 2016 — SECURE Trial: Isavuconazole for Invasive Aspergillosis/Mucormycosis",detail:"Pivotal non-inferiority trial comparing isavuconazole to voriconazole for primary treatment of invasive aspergillosis. Isavuconazole was non-inferior (overall mortality 18.6% vs 20.2%). KEY ADVANTAGES of isavuconazole: no QTc prolongation (actually shortens QTc), no hepatotoxicity signal, no visual disturbances, IV formulation without cyclodextrin (safe in renal impairment), and predictable pharmacokinetics allowing less frequent TDM.",sourceIds:["secure-trial"]},{name:"Marr et al., Ann Intern Med 2015 — Voriconazole + Anidulafungin Combination vs Voriconazole Monotherapy",detail:"RCT examining combination antifungal therapy for invasive aspergillosis. Primary endpoint (6-week mortality) showed a trend favoring combination (19.3% vs 27.5%, p=0.087) that did not reach significance. POST-HOC subgroup analysis: patients with galactomannan-proven IA had significant mortality benefit with combination (15.7% vs 27.3%). This trial is the basis for considering combination therapy in select high-risk patients, though not universally recommended.",sourceIds:["marr-2015-voriconazole-anidulafungin"]}],riskFactors:"Candidemia: Central venous catheters (strongest modifiable risk factor), broad-spectrum antibiotics (especially anti-anaerobic agents), ICU stay >3 days, TPN, recent abdominal surgery (especially GI anastomotic leak), neutropenia, immunosuppression (steroids, chemotherapy), renal failure requiring dialysis, Candida colonization at multiple sites (colonization index), prior fluconazole exposure (selects for resistant species). Invasive aspergillosis: Prolonged neutropenia (>10 days ANC <500), allogeneic HSCT (especially with GVHD requiring steroids), solid organ transplant (lung transplant highest risk), hematologic malignancy (AML induction, MDS), chronic high-dose corticosteroids (≥20mg prednisone ≥3 weeks), inherited or acquired immunodeficiency (CGD, AIDS with CD4 <100), novel immunotherapies (ibrutinib, ruxolitinib — impair macrophage/neutrophil function)."},subcategories:[{id:"candidemia",name:"Candidemia & Invasive Candidiasis",definition:"Candidemia is defined as ≥1 blood culture positive for Candida species. Invasive candidiasis encompasses candidemia plus deep-seated organ involvement (endocarditis, osteomyelitis, endophthalmitis, hepatosplenic candidiasis, CNS candidiasis). Candidemia requires treatment even if catheter-related and patient appears clinically stable — untreated candidemia has mortality >40%. All patients with candidemia must have an ophthalmologic exam (endophthalmitis in 10–15%) and repeat blood cultures every 24–48 hours until clearance.",clinicalPresentation:"Candidemia often presents identically to bacterial sepsis: fever, tachycardia, hypotension, leukocytosis. NO pathognomonic features distinguish it from bacteremia clinically. Key distinguishing features that should raise suspicion: persistent fever despite broad-spectrum antibacterials in an ICU patient with risk factors, new-onset endophthalmitis symptoms (eye pain, floaters, visual changes), hepatosplenic candidiasis presenting as persistent fever and elevated ALP in a recovering neutropenic patient, skin lesions (erythematous papules/nodules with central pallor) in disseminated disease. Candiduria is common in ICU patients and usually represents colonization — treat only if symptomatic or high-risk (neutropenic, renal transplant, undergoing urologic surgery).",diagnostics:"Blood cultures: GOLD STANDARD but sensitivity only 50–75% for candidemia. Time to positivity usually 2–5 days (slower than most bacteria). Species identification and susceptibility testing are ESSENTIAL — guide de-escalation and predict resistance. β-D-glucan (BDG): Serum marker for invasive fungal infection, sensitivity 65–85% for candidiasis. Useful as adjunct but many false positives (hemodialysis, albumin infusion, surgical gauze, bacteremia with Streptococcus). NOT specific for Candida — elevated in aspergillosis, PJP, and other fungi. T2Candida panel: PCR-based rapid diagnostic (3–5 hours), detects C. albicans/tropicalis, C. parapsilosis, C. glabrata/krusei directly from blood. Sensitivity 91%, specificity 98%. Major advantage: faster species identification allowing earlier targeted therapy. Repeat blood cultures: Obtain every 24–48 hours until clearance. Duration of therapy is counted from the FIRST NEGATIVE blood culture, not from treatment initiation. Echocardiography: Consider TTE in all candidemia patients, TEE if prosthetic valves, prolonged candidemia, or clinical suspicion of endocarditis.",empiricTherapy:[{line:"Preferred — First-Line Empiric",options:[{drug:"micafungin",regimen:"Micafungin 100 mg IV once daily",notes:"IDSA 2016 first-line for candidemia regardless of severity or species. Echinocandins preferred over fluconazole because: (1) broader spectrum covering C. glabrata and C. krusei, (2) fungicidal vs. fungistatic, (3) better outcomes in RCTs (Reboli 2007). Continue until species identification and susceptibility allow de-escalation.",monographId:"micafungin",id:"fungal-infections/candidemia/preferred-first-line-empiric/micafungin-1"},{drug:"caspofungin",regimen:"Caspofungin 70 mg IV load × 1, then 50 mg IV daily",notes:"Alternative echinocandin. Equivalent efficacy to micafungin. Loading dose required on day 1. More drug interactions (cyclosporine — hepatotoxicity risk, rifampin — reduces caspofungin levels). Dose adjust for hepatic impairment (Child-Pugh B: 35 mg daily after load).",id:"fungal-infections/candidemia/preferred-first-line-empiric/caspofungin-2"},{drug:"anidulafungin",regimen:"Anidulafungin 200 mg IV load × 1, then 100 mg IV daily",notes:"Third echinocandin option. Best evidence from the Reboli NEJM 2007 trial. No hepatic or renal dose adjustment needed. Non-enzymatic degradation (no CYP metabolism) means fewest drug interactions of the echinocandins. Preferred when drug interactions are a concern.",id:"fungal-infections/candidemia/preferred-first-line-empiric/anidulafungin-3"}]},{line:"Alternative — De-escalation / Fluconazole-Susceptible",options:[{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Fluconazole 800 mg (12 mg/kg) IV/PO load × 1, then 400 mg (6 mg/kg) IV/PO daily",notes:"STEP-DOWN therapy once: (1) patient is clinically stable, (2) Candida species confirmed susceptible (MIC ≤2 mcg/mL), (3) blood cultures are clearing, (4) no metastatic complications. Loading dose is critical and frequently omitted. IV-to-PO switch: bioavailability is ~90%, so same dose PO. NOT appropriate for C. glabrata (dose-dependent susceptibility), C. krusei (intrinsically resistant), or critically ill patients on vasopressors.",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/candidemia/alternative-de-escalation-fluconazole-susceptibl/fluconazole-1"}]},{line:"Reserve — Amphotericin B",options:[{drug:"amphotericin-b",regimen:"Amphotericin B liposomal (AmBisome) 3–5 mg/kg IV daily",notes:"Reserve for: (1) echinocandin-resistant Candida (rare but increasing), (2) CNS candidiasis (echinocandins do not penetrate CNS), (3) endocarditis (in combination), (4) C. auris with pan-echinocandin resistance. Always use LIPID formulation — conventional amphotericin B deoxycholate has unacceptable nephrotoxicity. Monitor: daily BMP (creatinine, potassium, magnesium), CBC.",monographId:"amphotericin-b",id:"fungal-infections/candidemia/reserve-amphotericin-b/amphotericin-b-1"}]},{line:"Duration & Source Control",options:[{drug:"",regimen:"Duration: 14 days from FIRST NEGATIVE blood culture + resolution of symptoms/signs",notes:"CVC removal: Strongly recommended within 24–48 hours when feasible. CVC retention is associated with higher mortality and prolonged candidemia. If CVC cannot be removed (e.g., limited access), ensure echinocandin therapy and consider locking solutions for biofilm. Ophthalmologic exam: Within 1 week of diagnosis in non-neutropenic patients, within 1 week of neutrophil recovery in neutropenic patients. If endophthalmitis present: extend treatment to ≥4–6 weeks and consider intravitreal amphotericin B.",id:"fungal-infections/candidemia/duration-source-control/option-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[{organism:"C. albicans (fluconazole-susceptible)",preferred:"Echinocandin → de-escalate to fluconazole 400 mg PO daily once stable + cultures clearing",alternative:"Fluconazole 800 mg load, then 400 mg daily (if non-critically ill, stable, no prior azole exposure)",notes:"Most common species (~50%). Predictably fluconazole-susceptible. De-escalation from echinocandin to fluconazole is recommended once susceptibility confirmed and patient stable. Fluconazole has excellent bioavailability allowing early IV-to-PO conversion."},{organism:"C. glabrata",preferred:"Echinocandin (micafungin 100 mg IV daily or caspofungin or anidulafungin) for full duration",alternative:"If susceptible: high-dose fluconazole 800 mg daily (MIC ≤32 AND confirmed susceptible-dose dependent). Voriconazole 200 mg BID if fluconazole-resistant but voriconazole-susceptible.",notes:"Second most common species (15–25%). Intrinsically fluconazole dose-dependent susceptible (MIC 8–32) and increasingly resistant (10–15% now resistant). ALWAYS obtain susceptibility testing. FKS mutations confer echinocandin resistance (1–3% overall, but 8–12% in patients with prior echinocandin exposure). If echinocandin-resistant: amphotericin B."},{organism:"C. krusei",preferred:"Echinocandin for full duration",alternative:"Voriconazole 200 mg IV/PO BID (load 400 mg BID × 2 doses)",notes:"INTRINSICALLY fluconazole-resistant (chromosomal resistance mechanism). Echinocandin preferred because of consistent susceptibility. Voriconazole is an alternative with good in vitro activity. Never use fluconazole — will fail regardless of dose."},{organism:"C. parapsilosis",preferred:"Fluconazole 800 mg load, then 400 mg daily",alternative:"Echinocandin if fluconazole-resistant (rare)",notes:"UNIQUE among Candida: echinocandins have higher MICs against C. parapsilosis (intrinsic FKS polymorphism). Clinical significance debated — most experts still start echinocandin empirically then de-escalate to fluconazole once species identified. Strong association with CVC biofilm — CVC removal especially important. Also associated with TPN and neonates."},{organism:"C. auris",preferred:"Echinocandin at standard dosing (micafungin 100 mg IV daily preferred)",alternative:"If echinocandin-resistant: amphotericin B liposomal 3–5 mg/kg IV daily. If pan-resistant: combination therapy (consider amphotericin B + flucytosine, or investigate newer agents)",notes:"EMERGING MDR THREAT. >90% fluconazole-resistant, 30–40% amphotericin B-resistant, ~5% echinocandin-resistant. Requires STRICT contact precautions and infection control measures. Often misidentified by conventional methods — requires MALDI-TOF or molecular identification. CDC urgent threat pathogen. Susceptibility testing mandatory for all isolates. Healthcare facility outbreaks documented — persistent environmental contamination."}],pearls:["The single most impactful intervention in candidemia is EARLY CVC REMOVAL — within 24–48 hours. Delayed removal independently predicts mortality. Fight for this in your interdisciplinary rounds.","Duration counting: 14 days starts from the FIRST NEGATIVE blood culture, NOT from antifungal initiation. If it takes 5 days for cultures to clear, total treatment will be ~19 days minimum. This is the most common duration error.","Loading doses for fluconazole (800 mg × 1) are frequently omitted but pharmacokinetically essential. Fluconazole has a long half-life (~30 hours) and without a loading dose takes 5–7 days to reach steady state. In candidemia, you cannot afford to wait.","Don't forget the eye exam. Candida endophthalmitis occurs in 10–15% of candidemia patients and changes the treatment duration (4–6 weeks minimum) and may require intravitreal therapy. It is a pharmacist's role to remind the team.","C. parapsilosis + echinocandin: Clinical data shows echinocandins still work clinically despite higher MICs, but many ID experts prefer fluconazole step-down once C. parapsilosis is confirmed. Know your institution's approach.","Echinocandin resistance in C. glabrata (FKS mutations) is more common than you think in patients with prior echinocandin exposure. If a patient has had echinocandins in the past 90 days and grows C. glabrata, request FKS mutation testing or at minimum interpret MICs carefully.","β-D-glucan can be falsely elevated by: hemodialysis filters (especially cellulose membranes), IV immunoglobulin, albumin, amoxicillin-clavulanate, Bactrim (TMP-SMX), piperacillin-tazobactam, surgical gauze, and bacteremia (especially Streptococcus). Know these before over-interpreting a positive result.","C. auris infection control: If your institution identifies C. auris, this is an infection control emergency. Requires contact precautions, dedicated equipment, daily chlorhexidine bathing, and enhanced environmental cleaning. Pharmacy role: ensure appropriate empiric therapy and notify infection prevention immediately."]},{id:"invasive-aspergillosis",name:"Invasive Pulmonary Aspergillosis",definition:"Invasive pulmonary aspergillosis (IPA) is a life-threatening mold infection predominantly caused by A. fumigatus in immunocompromised hosts. Characterized by tissue invasion with angioinvasion leading to hemorrhagic infarction, cavitation, and potential dissemination. Mortality 30–60% even with treatment, depending on immune status and time to diagnosis. A 'proven' diagnosis requires histopathology; 'probable' diagnosis per EORTC/MSG criteria combines host factors + clinical/radiologic features + mycologic evidence (galactomannan, culture, PCR).",clinicalPresentation:"Classic presentation in neutropenic patient: persistent fever despite broad-spectrum antibacterials for ≥96 hours, pleuritic chest pain, hemoptysis, dyspnea. CT chest findings: early — nodules with 'halo sign' (ground-glass opacity surrounding nodule, representing hemorrhagic infarction); late — 'air crescent sign' (crescent of air within cavity, seen during neutrophil recovery as necrotic tissue separates). Non-neutropenic immunocompromised patients (steroids, SOT recipients): presentation may be subacute with non-specific infiltrates, consolidation, or ground-glass opacities that mimic bacterial pneumonia or organizing pneumonia. High index of suspicion is critical. Tracheobronchial aspergillosis: ulcerative or pseudomembranous tracheobronchitis, particularly in lung transplant recipients — may be missed if bronchoscopy not performed.",diagnostics:"CT chest: HIGH-RESOLUTION CT is the imaging modality of choice. Obtain early (don't wait for conventional CXR progression). Halo sign in neutropenic patient is highly suggestive. Galactomannan (GM): Serum sensitivity 70–80% in hematologic malignancy/HSCT, but only 20–30% in SOT recipients (lower fungal burden). BAL galactomannan has higher sensitivity (80–90%). Use cutoff ≥1.0 ODI for BAL (more specific than ≥0.5). FALSE POSITIVES: piperacillin-tazobactam (less common with newer formulations but still occurs), cross-reactivity with other molds, mucositis/GI disruption, and dietary sources (Plasmalyte, some pasta products). β-D-glucan: Elevated in aspergillosis but non-specific. Aspergillus PCR: Increasingly validated, EORTC/MSG now includes as mycologic criterion. Can be performed on blood or BAL. Culture: Low sensitivity from blood (<1% positive), BAL culture positive in 30–60%. Positive respiratory culture in high-risk host should NOT be dismissed as colonization. Biopsy: Gold standard for proven diagnosis but often impractical due to thrombocytopenia and coagulopathy in the target population.",empiricTherapy:[{line:"Preferred — First-Line",options:[{drug:"voriconazole",regimen:"Voriconazole 6 mg/kg IV q12h × 2 doses (load), then 4 mg/kg IV q12h; PO: 200 mg q12h (≥40 kg)",notes:"IDSA 2016 first-line based on Herbrecht 2002 NEJM trial. THERAPEUTIC DRUG MONITORING IS MANDATORY — target trough 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL. Subtherapeutic levels (<1.0) associated with treatment failure, supratherapeutic (>5.5) associated with hepatotoxicity and neurotoxicity. Highly variable pharmacokinetics (CYP2C19 polymorphisms). Obtain first trough on day 5 of therapy. IV formulation contains sulfobutyl ether β-cyclodextrin (SBECD) — accumulates in CrCl <50, switch to PO if possible (PO bioavailability >96%).",monographId:"voriconazole",id:"fungal-infections/invasive-aspergillosis/preferred-first-line/voriconazole-1"}]},{line:"Alternative — First-Line",options:[{drug:"isavuconazole",regimen:"Isavuconazonium sulfate 372 mg (= 200 mg isavuconazole) IV/PO q8h × 6 doses (48 hr loading), then 372 mg IV/PO daily",notes:"Non-inferior to voriconazole per SECURE trial (Maertens 2016). KEY ADVANTAGES: (1) no QTc prolongation (SHORTENS QT — avoid if baseline short QT syndrome), (2) IV formulation WITHOUT cyclodextrin (safe in renal impairment), (3) fewer visual disturbances, (4) less hepatotoxicity, (5) more predictable PKs (TDM less critical but still recommended in some populations). ALSO active against Mucorales (unlike voriconazole) — useful when diagnosis uncertain between aspergillosis and mucormycosis. Becoming many centers' preferred first-line over voriconazole.",id:"fungal-infections/invasive-aspergillosis/alternative-first-line/isavuconazole-1"}]},{line:"Alternative — Echinocandin Combination",options:[{drug:"micafungin",regimen:"Voriconazole (standard dosing) + Micafungin 150 mg IV daily OR Caspofungin 70/50 mg IV daily",notes:"Combination therapy based on Marr 2015 trial: trend toward mortality benefit (19.3% vs 27.5%) that was not statistically significant overall, but subgroup with galactomannan-positive IA showed significant benefit. Consider combination in: (1) proven/probable IA with high fungal burden, (2) breakthrough on azole prophylaxis, (3) hematologic malignancy with prolonged neutropenia. NOT universally recommended — discuss with ID.",monographId:"micafungin",id:"fungal-infections/invasive-aspergillosis/alternative-echinocandin-combination/micafungin-1"}]},{line:"Salvage Therapy",options:[{drug:"amphotericin-b",regimen:"Amphotericin B liposomal (AmBisome) 3–5 mg/kg IV daily",notes:"Salvage for voriconazole/isavuconazole failure or intolerance. Higher doses (5 mg/kg) used in severe disease or CNS involvement. Also first-line if mucormycosis suspected (voriconazole has NO Mucorales activity). Monitor nephrotoxicity, electrolytes daily.",monographId:"amphotericin-b",id:"fungal-infections/invasive-aspergillosis/salvage-therapy/amphotericin-b-1"},{drug:"caspofungin",regimen:"Caspofungin 70 mg IV load, then 50 mg IV daily",notes:"Echinocandin monotherapy is salvage only — NOT adequate as primary therapy for aspergillosis (fungistatic, not fungicidal against Aspergillus). May be used in combination (see above) or when azoles and amphotericin B are not tolerable.",id:"fungal-infections/invasive-aspergillosis/salvage-therapy/caspofungin-2"}]},{line:"Duration & Monitoring",options:[{drug:"",regimen:"Minimum 6–12 weeks; continue until resolution of immunosuppression + radiographic improvement",notes:"Duration highly individualized. Minimum 6 weeks even with good response. In HSCT patients or those with ongoing immunosuppression, treatment often continues for months. Serial GM and CT chest q2–4 weeks to monitor response. IMMUNE RECONSTITUTION: neutrophil recovery is the most important prognostic factor. G-CSF and reduction of immunosuppression should be aggressively pursued. Secondary prophylaxis: after completing treatment, consider maintenance voriconazole/isavuconazole during subsequent immunosuppressive cycles.",id:"fungal-infections/invasive-aspergillosis/duration-monitoring/option-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[{organism:"Aspergillus fumigatus (susceptible)",preferred:"Voriconazole (with TDM) or isavuconazole",alternative:"Liposomal amphotericin B 3–5 mg/kg/day",notes:">90% of invasive aspergillosis. Generally susceptible to azoles, though azole-resistant A. fumigatus (TR34/L98H and TR46/Y121F/T289A mutations) is an emerging concern globally. Resistance prevalence: <2% US, 5–30% Netherlands/UK (environmental azole use in agriculture). If azole-resistant A. fumigatus suspected (treatment failure, known local resistance): liposomal amphotericin B or voriconazole + echinocandin combination."},{organism:"Aspergillus terreus",preferred:"Voriconazole or isavuconazole",alternative:"Echinocandin (caspofungin/micafungin) or isavuconazole + echinocandin",notes:"INTRINSICALLY amphotericin B-resistant (higher MICs, poor clinical outcomes with amphotericin B). Voriconazole or isavuconazole preferred. If species identification shows A. terreus, do NOT use amphotericin B as salvage — switch to azole-based therapy."},{organism:"Aspergillus niger",preferred:"Voriconazole or isavuconazole",alternative:"Liposomal amphotericin B",notes:"Generally susceptible to azoles and amphotericin B. More commonly causes otomycosis and aspergilloma than invasive disease. When invasive, treat similarly to A. fumigatus. May have slightly higher amphotericin B MICs — check susceptibility."}],pearls:["Voriconazole TDM is NOT optional — it is MANDATORY. The therapeutic window is narrow (1.0–5.5 mcg/mL) and interpatient variability is enormous due to CYP2C19 polymorphisms. Poor metabolizers: toxic levels on standard doses. Ultra-rapid metabolizers: subtherapeutic. Get the first trough on day 5, then weekly until stable.","Isavuconazole is increasingly becoming the preferred first-line at many centers over voriconazole: no cyclodextrin in IV formulation (renal-safe), no visual disturbances, less hepatotoxicity, activity against Mucorales, and more predictable PKs. Know your institution's preferred agent.","Piperacillin-tazobactam can cause false-positive galactomannan — this has been a known issue for years. While newer manufacturing processes have reduced it, it still occurs. If GM turns positive in a patient on pip-tazo, interpret cautiously and consider confirmatory BAL GM.","The 'halo sign' on CT chest has a narrow diagnostic window — it's most visible in the first 5–7 days of infection and disappears as neutrophils recover. Early CT imaging is critical. Don't wait for CXR to show something before ordering CT.","Voriconazole + fluoroquinolone QTc risk: Voriconazole inhibits CYP3A4 and can increase fluoroquinolone levels. Monitor QTc closely if co-administered. Also: voriconazole + tacrolimus requires tacrolimus dose reduction by 50–66% and close TDM.","Isavuconazole SHORTENS the QTc interval. This is actually a contraindication if the patient has familial short QT syndrome (very rare). But it makes it the preferred azole in patients already on QT-prolonging medications.","Breakthrough aspergillosis on azole prophylaxis: If a patient develops aspergillosis while on posaconazole or voriconazole prophylaxis, check drug levels first (compliance/absorption issue?) then consider switching to a different class (amphotericin B) or combination therapy. Don't simply increase the dose of the same azole."]},{id:"antifungal-stewardship",name:"Antifungal Stewardship & De-escalation",definition:"Antifungal stewardship encompasses systematic interventions to optimize antifungal use, improve patient outcomes, reduce resistance, and control costs. Key domains: (1) empiric-to-targeted de-escalation, (2) IV-to-PO conversion, (3) duration optimization, (4) prophylaxis appropriateness review, (5) TDM-guided dosing. Antifungals account for significant pharmacy spend — echinocandins cost $100–400/day, liposomal amphotericin B $500–1500/day. Stewardship interventions can safely reduce costs by 20–40%.",clinicalPresentation:"N/A — this section covers stewardship principles, not a clinical syndrome.",diagnostics:"N/A — see candidemia and aspergillosis sections for diagnostic approaches.",empiricTherapy:[{line:"Stewardship — Echinocandin-to-Fluconazole De-escalation",options:[{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Switch echinocandin → fluconazole 400 mg PO daily",notes:"CRITERIA FOR SAFE DE-ESCALATION: (1) Candida species confirmed susceptible to fluconazole (C. albicans, C. tropicalis, C. parapsilosis with MIC ≤2), (2) patient clinically improving (afebrile, hemodynamically stable, off vasopressors), (3) blood cultures clearing, (4) no metastatic complications (endophthalmitis, endocarditis, osteomyelitis), (5) able to tolerate oral medications. Average time to de-escalation: 5–7 days. This is the single highest-impact antifungal stewardship intervention.",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/antifungal-stewardship/stewardship-echinocandin-to-fluconazole-de-escal/fluconazole-1"}]},{line:"Stewardship — IV-to-PO Azole Conversion",options:[{drug:"voriconazole",regimen:"Switch voriconazole IV → voriconazole 200 mg PO q12h",notes:"Voriconazole oral bioavailability >96% — IV offers no pharmacokinetic advantage over PO. Switch as soon as patient can tolerate oral medications. IMPORTANT: Avoid taking with high-fat meals (reduces absorption by 34%). Also: PO tablets may actually give MORE predictable levels than IV in patients with renal impairment (avoids cyclodextrin accumulation).",monographId:"voriconazole",id:"fungal-infections/antifungal-stewardship/stewardship-iv-to-po-azole-conversion/voriconazole-1"},{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Switch fluconazole IV → same dose PO",notes:"Fluconazole oral bioavailability ~90%. Same dose IV and PO. One of the easiest IV-to-PO conversions in all of infectious disease. No food restrictions. Pharmacy should proactively recommend this conversion.",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/antifungal-stewardship/stewardship-iv-to-po-azole-conversion/fluconazole-2"}]},{line:"Stewardship — Prophylaxis Review",options:[{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Review appropriateness of antifungal prophylaxis",notes:"Appropriate prophylaxis: (1) Fluconazole 400 mg daily for allogeneic HSCT (engraftment through day +75), (2) Posaconazole 300 mg daily for AML/MDS induction chemotherapy with expected neutropenia >7 days, (3) Fluconazole 400 mg daily for high-risk liver transplant recipients. INAPPROPRIATE (common): continuing prophylaxis beyond risk period, prophylaxis in ICU patients without neutropenia (routine fluconazole in surgical ICU not recommended by guidelines), prophylaxis based solely on positive BDG without clinical correlation.",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/antifungal-stewardship/stewardship-prophylaxis-review/fluconazole-1"}]},{line:"Stewardship — TDM Optimization",options:[{drug:"voriconazole",regimen:"Voriconazole trough target: 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL",notes:"TDM schedule: Day 5 (steady state), then weekly until therapeutic and stable, then with dose changes, interacting drug changes, or clinical failure. Subtherapeutic (<1.0): Increase dose by 50%. Supratherapeutic (>5.5): Hold 1 dose, reduce by 50%, recheck in 3–5 days. CYP2C19 genotyping: Consider in patients with extreme levels despite standard dosing (PM vs UM phenotype). Posaconazole: Trough >1.0 mcg/mL for prophylaxis, >1.0–1.5 for treatment. Itraconazole: Trough >0.5 for prophylaxis, >1.0 for treatment.",monographId:"voriconazole",id:"fungal-infections/antifungal-stewardship/stewardship-tdm-optimization/voriconazole-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[],pearls:["Echinocandin-to-fluconazole de-escalation in candidemia saves $200–350/day and is safe when criteria are met. This should be on every pharmacist's radar for every patient with candidemia. Set a calendar reminder for day 5 to reassess.","The 'antifungal timeout' at 72–96 hours: For patients started on empiric antifungals (especially in ICU), reassess at 72–96 hours with culture data, BDG result, and clinical response. If cultures negative, BDG negative, and alternative diagnosis identified → STOP antifungals. Many empiric courses can be safely discontinued.","Fluconazole drug interactions to flag proactively: (1) Warfarin — increases INR (inhibits CYP2C9), (2) Tacrolimus/cyclosporine — increases levels (CYP3A4), (3) Phenytoin — bidirectional interaction, (4) Statins — increased myopathy risk, (5) Sulfonylureas — hypoglycemia. These are high-frequency, clinically significant interactions that pharmacists should intercept.","Cost awareness: Micafungin ~$100–150/day, Caspofungin ~$150–300/day, Anidulafungin ~$150–250/day, Liposomal amphotericin B ~$500–1500/day, Fluconazole ~$5–15/day PO. Every day of unnecessary echinocandin or amphotericin B matters. Be the steward.","Azole resistance surveillance: If your institution sends susceptibility testing to a reference lab and turnaround is >5 days, work with microbiology to explore faster options (MALDI-TOF with susceptibility panels, molecular testing). Delayed susceptibility data delays de-escalation."]},{id:"cryptococcal-meningitis",name:"Cryptococcal Meningitis",definition:"CNS infection caused by Cryptococcus neoformans (most common, associated with HIV/AIDS) or C. gattii (can infect immunocompetent hosts, associated with Pacific Northwest). The most common cause of meningitis in HIV-positive patients globally. Classically presents as subacute meningitis with elevated intracranial pressure. Treatment follows a 3-phase approach: induction → consolidation → maintenance.",clinicalPresentation:"Subacute onset (1–2 weeks) of headache, fever, altered mental status, nausea/vomiting. Neck stiffness may be ABSENT (unlike bacterial meningitis). Elevated intracranial pressure is COMMON and is the primary cause of morbidity and mortality — presents with severe headache, visual changes (papilledema, CN VI palsy), vomiting, altered consciousness. Disseminated disease may involve skin (umbilicated papules resembling molluscum — classic in AIDS), lungs (nodules, consolidation), and rarely other organs. In HIV patients: typically CD4 <100 cells/μL. In non-HIV immunocompromised: transplant recipients on calcineurin inhibitors, chronic corticosteroids.",diagnostics:"Lumbar puncture: ESSENTIAL — and serves dual diagnostic and therapeutic purpose (pressure management). CSF findings: elevated opening pressure (>20 cmH2O in >70% of patients, often >30–40), lymphocytic pleocytosis (may be minimal in severely immunosuppressed), low glucose, elevated protein. India ink: Classic test, sensitivity 60–80% in HIV patients (lower in non-HIV). Being replaced by antigen testing. CSF cryptococcal antigen (CrAg): Sensitivity >95%, specificity >95%. Lateral flow assay (LFA) preferred — rapid (10 min), inexpensive, highly accurate. GOLD STANDARD diagnostic test. CSF culture: Positive in >95% of HIV-associated cases. Also quantitative culture useful for monitoring clearance (early fungicidal activity). Serum CrAg: Sensitivity >95% for meningitis. Useful as screening test in HIV patients with CD4 <100 before symptoms develop (screen-and-treat strategy). Repeat LPs: Therapeutic LPs to manage elevated ICP — remove CSF to normalize pressure (<20 cmH2O or 50% reduction if very high). Daily LPs may be needed in severe cases.",empiricTherapy:[{line:"Preferred — Induction (HIV-associated)",options:[{drug:"amphotericin-b",regimen:"Amphotericin B liposomal 3–4 mg/kg IV daily + Flucytosine 25 mg/kg PO q6h × 2 weeks",notes:"ACTHUNG trial + AMBITION trial evidence. Amphotericin B + flucytosine is the MOST EFFECTIVE induction regimen, achieving the fastest CSF sterilization (~1 week). Flucytosine is critical — do NOT omit. If flucytosine unavailable, amphotericin B + fluconazole 800 mg daily is an alternative but inferior induction. Monitor flucytosine levels (target peak 30–80 mcg/mL), CBC (myelosuppression), and renal function daily.",monographId:"amphotericin-b",id:"fungal-infections/cryptococcal-meningitis/preferred-induction-hiv-associated/amphotericin-b-1"}]},{line:"Alternative — Induction (Resource-Limited)",options:[{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Fluconazole 1200 mg PO daily + Flucytosine 25 mg/kg PO q6h × 2 weeks",notes:"ACTHUNG trial: High-dose fluconazole + flucytosine is the best oral-only induction option. Faster CSF sterilization than fluconazole monotherapy. Important in resource-limited settings without amphotericin B access. Also validated: single high-dose amphotericin B liposomal (10 mg/kg × 1) + flucytosine + fluconazole (AMBITION trial) as simplified induction.",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/cryptococcal-meningitis/alternative-induction-resource-limited/fluconazole-1"}]},{line:"Consolidation (Week 2–10)",options:[{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Fluconazole 400–800 mg PO daily × 8 weeks",notes:"Begin after successful 2-week induction (clinical improvement, CSF sterilizing). Higher dose (800 mg) preferred in HIV patients. Continue with ART optimization — but timing of ART initiation is critical (see pearls).",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/cryptococcal-meningitis/consolidation-week-2-10/fluconazole-1"}]},{line:"Maintenance (Week 10+)",options:[{drug:"fluconazole",regimen:"Fluconazole 200 mg PO daily — continue until CD4 >100 × 1 year + undetectable viral load",notes:"Secondary prophylaxis. Can discontinue once immune reconstitution achieved: CD4 >100 for ≥1 year on ART with suppressed viral load. If CD4 drops below 100 again, restart maintenance fluconazole.",monographId:"fluconazole",id:"fungal-infections/cryptococcal-meningitis/maintenance-week-10/fluconazole-1"}]},{line:"Adjunctive — ICP Management",options:[{drug:"",regimen:"Therapeutic lumbar punctures: daily or as needed to maintain opening pressure <20 cmH2O",notes:"ELEVATED ICP IS THE PRIMARY KILLER in cryptococcal meningitis. Aggressive pressure management with serial LPs is essential. Remove enough CSF to achieve OP <20 or 50% reduction. VP shunt or lumbar drain for refractory elevated ICP. DO NOT use corticosteroids for ICP management in cryptococcal meningitis — the Day et al. NEJM 2014 trial showed dexamethasone INCREASED mortality.",id:"fungal-infections/cryptococcal-meningitis/adjunctive-icp-management/option-1"}]}],organismSpecific:[{organism:"C. neoformans (HIV-associated)",preferred:"Liposomal amphotericin B + flucytosine × 2 weeks → fluconazole 400–800 mg × 8 weeks → fluconazole 200 mg maintenance",alternative:"Fluconazole 1200 mg + flucytosine × 2 weeks if amphotericin B not available",notes:"Most common. Serum CrAg screening for all HIV patients with CD4 <100 is cost-effective and reduces mortality. TIMING OF ART: Delay ART initiation to 4–6 weeks AFTER starting antifungal induction. Earlier ART increases risk of immune reconstitution inflammatory syndrome (IRIS) and death."},{organism:"C. gattii",preferred:"Same induction as C. neoformans. Longer consolidation may be needed (consider 6–18 months total)",alternative:"Surgery for large cryptococcomas",notes:"Can infect immunocompetent hosts. Associated with Pacific Northwest (BC, Oregon, Washington). Forms larger cryptococcomas (mass lesions) more frequently than C. neoformans. May require neurosurgical intervention. Generally more resistant to fluconazole — consider higher doses and longer treatment."}],pearls:["THE MOST IMPORTANT INTERVENTION in cryptococcal meningitis is aggressive ICP management with serial LPs. Elevated ICP causes most early deaths. Do NOT rely on mannitol or steroids — they don't work here. Steroids INCREASE mortality (Day et al., NEJM 2014).","ART timing in HIV-associated cryptococcal meningitis: DO NOT start ART immediately. The COAT trial (Boulware et al., NEJM 2014) showed that early ART (within 1–2 weeks) DOUBLED mortality compared to delayed ART (4–6 weeks). The risk of cryptococcal IRIS is real and lethal.","Flucytosine is the most commonly omitted drug in cryptococcal meningitis treatment, yet it is the MOST IMPACTFUL addition to amphotericin B. It accelerates CSF sterilization from ~14 days to ~7 days. If your institution doesn't stock it, request it. Dose adjust for renal impairment. Monitor levels if available (peak 30–80 mcg/mL).","Screen-and-treat strategy: In HIV-positive patients newly diagnosed with CD4 <100, check serum CrAg. If positive but asymptomatic, perform LP to rule out subclinical meningitis. If LP negative, pre-emptive fluconazole 800 mg × 2 weeks then 400 mg × 8 weeks prevents progression to meningitis.","The AMBITION trial (Jarvis et al., NEJM 2022) validated a simplified induction: single high-dose liposomal amphotericin B (10 mg/kg × 1 dose) + flucytosine + fluconazole. Non-inferior to standard 7-day amphotericin B + flucytosine. This is a game-changer for resource-limited settings and simplifies logistics enormously."]}],drugMonographs:[{id:"fluconazole",name:"Fluconazole",brandNames:"Diflucan",drugClass:"Triazole antifungal",mechanismOfAction:"Inhibits fungal cytochrome P450 enzyme 14-α-demethylase (CYP51/lanosterol demethylase), blocking conversion of lanosterol to ergosterol. Ergosterol depletion disrupts fungal cell membrane integrity, increasing permeability and inhibiting cell growth. FUNGISTATIC against Candida (does not kill, inhibits growth). Selective for fungal CYP51 over human CYP enzymes, but still has significant CYP450 inhibition in humans (CYP2C9, CYP2C19, CYP3A4).",spectrum:"Candida albicans (excellent), C. tropicalis (good), C. parapsilosis (excellent — preferred agent), C. lusitaniae (good). LIMITED/RESISTANT: C. glabrata (dose-dependent susceptibility, 10–15% resistant), C. krusei (INTRINSICALLY RESISTANT — never use), C. auris (>90% resistant). NO activity against: Aspergillus spp., Mucorales, Scedosporium, Fusarium. Good CNS penetration (~70% of serum levels — useful for cryptococcal meningitis, NOT adequate for aspergillosis which requires voriconazole).",dosing:{candidemia:"Loading: 800 mg (12 mg/kg) IV/PO × 1, then 400 mg (6 mg/kg) IV/PO daily",mucosal_candidiasis:"Oropharyngeal: 200 mg × 1, then 100 mg daily × 7–14 days. Esophageal: 400 mg × 1, then 200–400 mg daily × 14–21 days",cryptococcal_consolidation:"400–800 mg PO daily × 8 weeks (after induction with amphotericin B)",cryptococcal_maintenance:"200 mg PO daily until CD4 >100 × 1 year + viral suppression",prophylaxis_HSCT:"400 mg PO daily from conditioning through day +75 (or until engraftment)",candiduria:"200–400 mg daily × 14 days (only if symptomatic or high-risk)"},renalAdjustment:"CrCl >50: No adjustment. CrCl ≤50 (not on dialysis): Reduce maintenance dose by 50% (loading dose remains full). Hemodialysis: 100% of dose after each session (fluconazole is significantly dialyzed, ~50% removed per session). CVVH/CVVHD: Standard dosing (200–400 mg daily) — dialysis clearance approximates normal GFR.",hepaticAdjustment:"Use with caution in hepatic impairment. No specific dose adjustment recommended, but monitor LFTs closely. Hepatotoxicity is rare but potentially fatal — idiosyncratic, not dose-dependent. Discontinue if ALT >5× ULN or symptomatic hepatitis.",adverseEffects:{common:"Nausea (7–10%), headache (5%), abdominal pain (3%), diarrhea (3%), rash (2%). Generally well-tolerated — best tolerated of all systemic antifungals.",serious:"Hepatotoxicity (rare, <1%, but can be fatal — cholestatic or hepatocellular), QTc prolongation (dose-dependent, clinically significant at high doses ≥800 mg), Stevens-Johnson syndrome (very rare), alopecia (dose-dependent, reversible, seen with prolonged high-dose therapy).",rare:"Adrenal insufficiency (all azoles can suppress steroidogenesis, more common with ketoconazole), agranulocytosis, anaphylaxis."},drugInteractions:["WARFARIN (CYP2C9 inhibition): Increases INR significantly — reduce warfarin dose by 25–50% and monitor INR within 3–5 days. One of the most common clinically significant fluconazole interactions.","TACROLIMUS / CYCLOSPORINE (CYP3A4 inhibition): Increases calcineurin inhibitor levels. Monitor closely and reduce tacrolimus dose by ~50% when starting fluconazole.","PHENYTOIN (bidirectional CYP2C9): Fluconazole increases phenytoin levels AND phenytoin may reduce fluconazole efficacy. Monitor both levels.","STATINS (CYP3A4): Increased risk of rhabdomyolysis with simvastatin, lovastatin (contraindicated). Atorvastatin: use with caution, consider dose reduction.","SULFONYLUREAS (CYP2C9): Increased hypoglycemia risk with glipizide, glyburide. Monitor blood glucose and consider dose reduction.","OPIOIDS — Methadone (CYP3A4/2B6): Increases methadone levels, risk of QTc prolongation and respiratory depression. Fentanyl: increased levels possible.","RIFAMPIN: Potent CYP inducer reduces fluconazole levels by ~25%. Consider increasing fluconazole dose to 800 mg daily if co-administered."],monitoring:"Baseline: LFTs, BMP (creatinine for dose adjustment), ECG if using high doses (≥800 mg) or concomitant QTc-prolonging drugs. During therapy: LFTs weekly for first month, then monthly. BMP if renal function changing. Repeat blood cultures q24–48h for candidemia until clearance. Fluconazole TDM: NOT routinely required (predictable linear pharmacokinetics), but can be useful in obese patients (>120 kg), patients on RRT, or when drug interactions are complex.",pregnancyLactation:"Category D (1st trimester) / Category C (2nd–3rd trimester). HIGH-DOSE fluconazole (≥400 mg) in first trimester associated with craniofacial and skeletal malformations (fluconazole embryopathy). Single-dose 150 mg for vaginal candidiasis appears safe. AVOID chronic high-dose use in pregnancy. Excreted in breast milk at concentrations similar to plasma — AAP considers compatible with breastfeeding at lower doses but consider risk/benefit at higher doses.",pharmacistPearls:["LOADING DOSE IS ESSENTIAL: Fluconazole half-life is ~30 hours. Without a loading dose (800 mg for serious infection), it takes 5–7 days to reach steady state. In candidemia, this delay can be fatal. The loading dose is the single most commonly omitted step in fluconazole prescribing.","IV-to-PO conversion: Oral bioavailability ~90%. There is almost NEVER a pharmacokinetic reason to keep a patient on IV fluconazole if they can swallow. This is one of the easiest and most impactful IV-to-PO conversions you'll make. Same dose, same frequency.","Fluconazole does NOT cover Aspergillus — this seems obvious but the number of times empiric fluconazole is prescribed for suspected IPA in neutropenic patients is staggering. If you suspect aspergillosis, you need voriconazole, isavuconazole, or amphotericin B.","C. glabrata + fluconazole: The MIC breakpoint is ≤2 (susceptible), 4 (susceptible-dose dependent), ≥8 (resistant). 'Susceptible-dose dependent' means it MAY work at 800 mg/day but there's little clinical data supporting this. Most experts use echinocandin for C. glabrata and avoid fluconazole entirely. Know your institution's antibiogram.","Alopecia occurs with prolonged fluconazole use (>3 months) and is dose-dependent. Patients are often distressed — reassure them it's reversible after discontinuation. It's NOT a reason to stop medically necessary therapy, but they should be warned proactively."]},{id:"micafungin",name:"Micafungin",brandNames:"Mycamine",drugClass:"Echinocandin antifungal (lipopeptide)",mechanismOfAction:"Inhibits synthesis of β-(1,3)-D-glucan, an essential component of the fungal cell wall (not present in mammalian cells). This non-competitive inhibition of glucan synthase results in osmotic instability and cell lysis. FUNGICIDAL against Candida (kills, doesn't just inhibit). FUNGISTATIC against Aspergillus (inhibits hyphal tip growth). The unique mechanism of action means NO cross-resistance with azoles or amphotericin B.",spectrum:"EXCELLENT: Candida albicans, C. glabrata, C. tropicalis, C. krusei, C. dubliniensis. GOOD BUT HIGHER MICs: C. parapsilosis (intrinsic FKS polymorphism — MICs 0.5–2 vs. ≤0.06 for other species; clinical significance debated). Aspergillus spp. (fungistatic — NOT adequate as monotherapy, used in combination). NO ACTIVITY: Cryptococcus neoformans (no glucan synthase target), Mucorales (zygomycetes), Fusarium, Scedosporium, Trichosporon.",dosing:{candidemia:"100 mg IV once daily (no loading dose needed — steady state in ~4 days, but adequate levels achieved with first dose)",esophageal_candidiasis:"150 mg IV once daily",prophylaxis_HSCT:"50 mg IV once daily",aspergillosis_combination:"150 mg IV once daily (when used in combination with voriconazole for salvage/combination)"},renalAdjustment:"No dose adjustment required at any level of renal impairment including hemodialysis and CVVH. Micafungin is NOT dialyzable (high protein binding >99%, large molecular weight). This makes echinocandins the SIMPLEST antifungal to dose in renal impairment.",hepaticAdjustment:"Mild-moderate (Child-Pugh A/B): No dose adjustment. Severe (Child-Pugh C): Limited data — use with caution, no specific dose reduction recommended but monitor closely. Micafungin has been associated with hepatotoxicity (see adverse effects).",adverseEffects:{common:"Nausea (3%), vomiting (2%), diarrhea (2%), headache (2%), phlebitis at infusion site (2%), abnormal LFTs (3–5%). Generally VERY well-tolerated — the best safety profile of any systemic antifungal.",serious:"Hepatotoxicity (elevated ALT/AST, rare hepatocellular injury — FDA black box warning in Japan, not US), hemolytic anemia (rare), anaphylaxis (<1%), histamine-like infusion reactions.",rare:"Renal toxicity (uncommon, much less than amphotericin B), leukopenia, thrombocytopenia. Animal studies showed hepatocellular tumors at doses >therapeutic — no human signal to date, but this is why some guidelines limit prophylaxis duration."},drugInteractions:["MINIMAL drug interactions — major advantage over azoles. Echinocandins do not significantly interact with CYP450 enzymes.","SIROLIMUS: Micafungin may increase sirolimus exposure by ~20%. Monitor sirolimus levels when initiating or discontinuing micafungin.","NIFEDIPINE: Micafungin may increase nifedipine levels. Monitor for hypotension if co-administered.","ITRACONAZOLE: Micafungin may slightly increase itraconazole levels. Likely not clinically significant.","Note: Unlike caspofungin, micafungin does NOT have the hepatotoxicity interaction with cyclosporine. This makes micafungin preferred over caspofungin in transplant patients on calcineurin inhibitors."],monitoring:"Baseline: LFTs, CBC. During therapy: LFTs weekly (watch for hepatocellular pattern). CBC if prolonged therapy. Micafungin TDM: NOT routinely available or recommended — standard dosing is generally adequate. No renal monitoring needed for drug-related nephrotoxicity. For candidemia: repeat blood cultures every 24–48 hours until clearance.",pregnancyLactation:"Category C. Animal studies showed visceral abnormalities at high doses. Very limited human data. Use only if benefit outweighs risk. Consider amphotericin B (Category B) as the preferred antifungal in pregnancy for serious fungal infections. Unknown if excreted in breast milk.",pharmacistPearls:["Micafungin 100 mg IV daily for candidemia is the SIMPLEST antifungal to dose: no loading dose, no renal adjustment, no hepatic adjustment for mild-moderate disease, minimal drug interactions. This is why many institutions prefer it as the first-line echinocandin.","Echinocandins do NOT cover Cryptococcus — this is a critical distinction. If a patient has candidemia and you're using micafungin, that's correct. If they have cryptococcal meningitis, micafungin is useless. The cell wall target (β-glucan) is present in Candida and Aspergillus but NOT Cryptococcus.","C. parapsilosis + echinocandin: The higher MICs are real (0.5–2 vs. ≤0.06 for C. albicans), but clinical outcomes data are mixed. The IDSA 2016 guidelines still accept echinocandin for C. parapsilosis but recommend considering fluconazole step-down once species identified. Know your institution's practice pattern.","Micafungin vs. caspofungin in transplant patients: Micafungin is preferred because caspofungin + cyclosporine can cause hepatotoxicity. Micafungin doesn't have this interaction. This is a pharmacist-level nuance that many physicians don't know.","For candidemia, do NOT stop micafungin just because blood cultures are negative. The 14-day clock starts from the first negative culture. If it takes 5 days to clear, total therapy is at minimum 19 days. Premature discontinuation is a common error."]},{id:"voriconazole",name:"Voriconazole",brandNames:"Vfend",drugClass:"Triazole antifungal (second-generation)",mechanismOfAction:"Same mechanism as fluconazole (CYP51/14-α-demethylase inhibition) but with broader affinity for fungal CYP51 enzymes, including Aspergillus CYP51. This broader binding explains the extended spectrum compared to fluconazole. FUNGICIDAL against Aspergillus (unique among azoles). FUNGISTATIC against Candida. More potent CYP450 inhibitor in humans than fluconazole — more drug interactions.",spectrum:"EXCELLENT: Aspergillus spp. (A. fumigatus, A. flavus, A. niger — first-line), Candida spp. (all species including C. krusei and many C. glabrata), Scedosporium apiospermum, Fusarium spp. (variable). GOOD: Rare molds where other options limited. NO ACTIVITY: Mucorales (zygomycetes — Rhizopus, Mucor) — this is a CRITICAL gap. If mucormycosis is in the differential, use isavuconazole or amphotericin B instead. Cryptococcus: active in vitro but NOT first-line (fluconazole preferred for CNS penetration at standard doses).",dosing:{invasive_aspergillosis:"IV: 6 mg/kg q12h × 2 doses (load), then 4 mg/kg q12h. PO (≥40 kg): 400 mg q12h × 2 doses (load), then 200 mg q12h",candidemia:"Same dosing as aspergillosis (used less commonly, usually for fluconazole-resistant species)",esophageal_candidiasis:"200 mg PO q12h × 14–21 days"},renalAdjustment:"Oral: No renal adjustment needed (not renally cleared). IV: AVOID IV formulation if CrCl <50 mL/min — the SBECD (sulfobutyl ether β-cyclodextrin) vehicle accumulates and is nephrotoxic. Switch to PO (bioavailability >96%, so PO is pharmacokinetically equivalent). If IV is absolutely required in renal impairment: monitor SBECD levels if available, or accept the risk with close renal monitoring. Hemodialysis: Voriconazole is not significantly dialyzed, but SBECD is. If using IV on dialysis, administer after sessions. PO preferred.",hepaticAdjustment:"Mild-moderate (Child-Pugh A/B): Use standard loading dose, REDUCE maintenance by 50%. Severe (Child-Pugh C): Avoid if possible — extensive hepatic metabolism makes levels unpredictable. If used, reduce maintenance dose by 50% and monitor TDM closely. Voriconazole-associated hepatotoxicity is dose-dependent and correlated with trough >5.5 mcg/mL.",adverseEffects:{common:"Visual disturbances (30%! — photopsia, color changes, blurred vision; reversible, occur within 30 min of dosing, resolve in 30–60 min; due to retinal photoreceptor inhibition), hepatotoxicity (elevated LFTs in 10–15%), rash (6%), nausea (5%), headache.",serious:"Hepatotoxicity (including hepatic failure, correlated with trough >5.5), QTc prolongation (risk increases with supratherapeutic levels), periostitis/fluorosis (with prolonged use >6 months — bone pain, elevated fluoride), phototoxicity (severe sunburn risk — sunscreen + photoprotection mandatory), squamous cell carcinoma (associated with prolonged use >1 year, especially in transplant patients — dermatologic screening recommended).",rare:"Stevens-Johnson syndrome/TEN, pancreatitis, optic neuritis, hallucinations (trough >5.5)."},drugInteractions:["TACROLIMUS (CYP3A4): Voriconazole increases tacrolimus levels 2–3×. REDUCE tacrolimus dose by 50–66% and check levels within 3 days. This is the single most dangerous voriconazole interaction in transplant patients.","CYCLOSPORINE (CYP3A4): Increases levels ~1.7×. Reduce cyclosporine dose by 50% and monitor levels.","SIROLIMUS: CONTRAINDICATED — voriconazole increases sirolimus levels >10×. Must use alternative immunosuppressant or alternative antifungal.","PHENYTOIN / CARBAMAZEPINE: Potent CYP inducers dramatically reduce voriconazole levels. Avoid combination if possible. If necessary, increase voriconazole dose to 5 mg/kg IV q12h or 400 mg PO q12h and follow TDM closely.","RIFAMPIN / RIFABUTIN: Rifampin CONTRAINDICATED — reduces voriconazole levels by >95%. Rifabutin: reduce rifabutin dose, increase voriconazole dose, and monitor both levels.","WARFARIN (CYP2C9): Increases INR. More potent interaction than fluconazole. Monitor INR closely.","QTc-PROLONGING DRUGS: Additive risk. Avoid or closely monitor ECG with fluoroquinolones, ondansetron (high-dose), methadone, certain antipsychotics.","EFAVIRENZ: CONTRAINDICATED at standard doses — dramatic bidirectional interaction. If necessary, increase voriconazole to 400 mg q12h and reduce efavirenz to 300 mg daily (complex, TDM essential).","OPIOIDS — Methadone, oxycodone, fentanyl: Increased levels via CYP3A4 inhibition. Monitor for sedation/respiratory depression."],monitoring:"THERAPEUTIC DRUG MONITORING IS MANDATORY. Trough target: 1.0–5.5 mcg/mL. First trough: Day 5 of therapy (steady state reached by day 5–7). Frequency: Weekly until stable therapeutic range, then with dose changes, addition/removal of interacting drugs, or clinical failure/toxicity. LFTs: Baseline, then weekly for first month, then bimonthly. ECG: Baseline and periodically (QTc). Visual assessment: Document visual symptoms at each encounter. Dermatologic exam: Every 6 months if prolonged therapy (skin cancer screening). Fluoride level: If >6 months of therapy and bone pain.",pregnancyLactation:"Category D — TERATOGENIC. Animal studies show cleft palate, hydronephrosis, skeletal abnormalities at therapeutic doses. CONTRAINDICATED in pregnancy. Women of childbearing potential should use effective contraception during therapy and for 30 days after discontinuation. Unknown if excreted in breast milk — avoid during lactation.",pharmacistPearls:["Voriconazole TDM is the pharmacist's bread and butter in antifungal stewardship. The therapeutic window (1.0–5.5) is narrow and the interpatient variability is enormous. CYP2C19 poor metabolizers (~15–20% of Asian patients, ~3–5% of Caucasians) can have toxic levels on standard doses. Ultra-rapid metabolizers can be subtherapeutic. YOU are the TDM expert — own this.","Visual disturbances (photopsia) occur in ~30% of patients — they see bright spots, color changes, or halos around lights. This is NOT dangerous and is reversible. However, patients are often terrified. Counsel proactively: 'You may notice visual changes about 30 minutes after each dose — this is expected, temporary (resolves in ~1 hour), and not harmful to your eyes.'","IV-to-PO conversion: Voriconazole oral bioavailability is >96%. The IV formulation adds SBECD nephrotoxicity risk. Switch to PO as soon as the patient can swallow. This is one case where PO is actually SAFER than IV.","Voriconazole + sunlight = severe phototoxicity and long-term skin cancer risk. Every patient on voriconazole needs SPF 50+ sunscreen, protective clothing, and UV-blocking sunglasses. For transplant patients on chronic voriconazole, annual dermatologic screening is recommended. This is a pharmacist counseling point that is frequently missed.","The voriconazole-sirolimus interaction is CONTRAINDICATED — not 'use with caution,' CONTRAINDICATED. Sirolimus levels increase >10× with voriconazole. If a transplant patient needs voriconazole, the immunosuppression regimen must be converted from sirolimus to an alternative (usually tacrolimus with dose reduction). Coordinate this with the transplant team proactively.","No Mucorales coverage: If the differential includes mucormycosis (e.g., diabetic patient with rhinocerebral disease, post-transplant with lung lesions where aspergillosis vs. mucormycosis unclear), do NOT use voriconazole empirically. Use isavuconazole (covers both) or amphotericin B. Voriconazole may actually be a RISK FACTOR for breakthrough mucormycosis in prophylaxis settings."]},{id:"amphotericin-b",name:"Amphotericin B (Liposomal)",brandNames:"AmBisome",drugClass:"Polyene antifungal (lipid formulation)",mechanismOfAction:"Binds to ergosterol in the fungal cell membrane, creating pores that increase membrane permeability, causing leakage of intracellular contents and cell death. FUNGICIDAL — directly damages the cell membrane. Also has immunomodulatory effects (enhances macrophage and neutrophil function). The liposomal formulation encapsulates amphotericin B in true liposomes, which preferentially deliver drug to fungal cell membranes and RES tissues, reducing renal and infusion toxicity compared to conventional amphotericin B deoxycholate. ALWAYS USE LIPID FORMULATION — conventional amphotericin B deoxycholate is nephrotoxic and should be avoided except when lipid formulations are unavailable.",spectrum:"BROADEST SPECTRUM of any antifungal. Candida spp. (all, including C. auris — though some resistance emerging), Aspergillus spp. (except A. terreus — INTRINSICALLY RESISTANT), Cryptococcus neoformans (essential for induction), Mucorales/Zygomycetes (Rhizopus, Mucor, Lichtheimia — first-line), Histoplasma, Blastomyces, Coccidioides (endemic mycoses), Fusarium, Trichosporon (variable). RESISTANT: A. terreus, some C. lusitaniae isolates.",dosing:{candidemia:"3 mg/kg IV daily (reserve for echinocandin-intolerant or resistant Candida, CNS candidiasis)",invasive_aspergillosis:"3–5 mg/kg IV daily (salvage therapy; higher doses for severe/CNS disease)",cryptococcal_meningitis:"3–4 mg/kg IV daily × 2 weeks (+ flucytosine) for induction",mucormycosis:"5–10 mg/kg IV daily (HIGH DOSE — mucormycosis requires aggressive dosing)",empiric_febrile_neutropenia:"3 mg/kg IV daily (when fungal infection suspected but not documented)",endemic_mycoses:"3–5 mg/kg IV daily for severe histoplasmosis, blastomycosis, coccidioidomycosis",single_dose_crypto_induction:"10 mg/kg IV × 1 dose (AMBITION trial protocol, with flucytosine + fluconazole)"},renalAdjustment:"No formal dose adjustment, but nephrotoxicity is the primary dose-limiting toxicity even with lipid formulations. Monitor creatinine daily. If creatinine doubles or rises above 2.5 mg/dL: consider dose reduction, alternate-day dosing, or switching to an alternative antifungal if clinically feasible. Aggressive pre-hydration: 500 mL–1L NS before each infusion significantly reduces nephrotoxicity. Hemodialysis: Not significantly dialyzed — no supplemental dosing needed. The nephrotoxicity mechanism is direct tubular injury (not dependent on GFR).",hepaticAdjustment:"No dose adjustment required. Hepatotoxicity is uncommon with amphotericin B. Liposomal formulation may cause transient LFT elevations but rarely clinically significant.",adverseEffects:{common:"Nephrotoxicity (15–30% with liposomal, vs. 50–60% with conventional), hypokalemia (30–40% — renal potassium wasting), hypomagnesemia (25%), infusion-related reactions (fever, rigors, chills — 15–20%, less with liposomal, premedicate with acetaminophen ± diphenhydramine ± meperidine for rigors), anemia (normocytic, from suppressed EPO production, 10–15%).",serious:"Acute kidney injury (can be severe, may require RRT in prolonged courses), cardiac arrhythmias (from electrolyte disturbances — fatal hypokalemia/hypomagnesemia), anaphylaxis (rare, 0.1%), cardiac arrest (with rapid infusion — NEVER give as IV push).",rare:"Hearing loss (especially with concurrent aminoglycosides), thrombocytopenia, hepatotoxicity, leukoencephalopathy (extremely rare)."},drugInteractions:["NEPHROTOXIC AGENTS (aminoglycosides, cyclosporine, tacrolimus, IV contrast, NSAIDs, vancomycin): Additive nephrotoxicity. Avoid concurrent nephrotoxins when possible. If unavoidable, aggressive hydration and daily renal monitoring.","POTASSIUM-WASTING DIURETICS (furosemide, hydrochlorothiazide): Additive hypokalemia — can be severe and fatal. Monitor potassium at least daily, replace aggressively.","CORTICOSTEROIDS: Additive hypokalemia. Very common co-administration in transplant patients — monitor K+ closely.","DIGOXIN: Amphotericin B-induced hypokalemia potentiates digoxin toxicity. Monitor both potassium and digoxin levels.","FLUCYTOSINE: Amphotericin B nephrotoxicity can reduce flucytosine clearance, increasing flucytosine toxicity (myelosuppression). Monitor flucytosine levels (peak 30–80 mcg/mL) and CBC when co-administered.","AZOLES (fluconazole, voriconazole): Theoretical antagonism (azoles deplete ergosterol, amphotericin B requires ergosterol for binding). Clinical significance unclear and generally not a concern in practice."],monitoring:"DAILY: BMP (creatinine, potassium, magnesium, bicarbonate). Potassium and magnesium replacement is an almost daily requirement during amphotericin B therapy — prepare standing replacement protocols. LFTs: Baseline and weekly. CBC: Baseline and weekly (anemia develops over 2–4 weeks). PRE-HYDRATION: 500 mL–1L NS prior to each infusion — reduces nephrotoxicity. This is non-negotiable. PREMEDICATIONS: Acetaminophen 650 mg PO + diphenhydramine 25–50 mg IV ± meperidine 25–50 mg IV (for rigors) given 30 min before infusion. Infusion rate: Over 2 hours (1 hour if tolerated). NEVER give as IV push.",pregnancyLactation:"Category B — the PREFERRED antifungal in pregnancy for serious infections. Extensive human experience with no documented teratogenicity. Used as first-line for candidemia and cryptococcal meningitis in pregnant patients. Liposomal formulation preferred over conventional for reduced toxicity. Unknown if excreted in breast milk, but systemically absorbed amounts in infant likely minimal.",pharmacistPearls:["ALWAYS use the LIPID formulation (AmBisome = liposomal, Abelcet = lipid complex). NEVER conventional amphotericin B deoxycholate (Fungizone) unless lipid formulations are truly unavailable. The nephrotoxicity difference is dramatic: ~20% vs ~50%. Medication errors between formulations are reported — verify product at dispensing.","Pre-hydration with NS is the single most effective intervention to prevent nephrotoxicity. It should be a standing order, not optional. 500 mL–1L NS before each dose, every single time.","Potassium and magnesium wasting is EXPECTED and UNIVERSAL with prolonged amphotericin B therapy. Set up standing replacement protocols. Patients will need 40–80 mEq KCl and 2–4g MgSO4 supplementation daily during treatment. Check levels daily and replace proactively. Hypomagnesemia makes hypokalemia refractory — always replace Mg first.","Amphotericin B is the pregnancy antifungal — Category B with decades of human safety data. When a pregnant patient needs treatment for candidemia, cryptococcal meningitis, or any serious fungal infection, amphotericin B is the go-to. Don't hesitate.","For mucormycosis, dose HIGH: 5–10 mg/kg/day. Standard 3 mg/kg dosing used for candidemia and aspergillosis is INADEQUATE for mucormycosis. Combined with surgical debridement, high-dose amphotericin B is the backbone of mucormycosis treatment.","The AMBITION trial's single-dose protocol (10 mg/kg × 1) for cryptococcal meningitis induction is a paradigm shift. One dose of liposomal amphotericin B with oral flucytosine + fluconazole was non-inferior to 7-day amphotericin B. This simplifies logistics enormously, especially in resource-limited settings. Know this protocol."]}]};export{e as FUNGAL_INFECTIONS};
